Comment: homeworkouts101 said "-
â–ªï¸Weighted T-Push Ups
-
TARGETS
1âƒ£Chest
2âƒ£Shoulders
3âƒ£Core
4âƒ£Glutes -
â–ªï¸Grab a pair of dumbbells and place them where your hands would normally go when performing a push-up. The dumbbells should be slightly wider than shoulder-width apart. Grasp the dumbbells and set yourself in a push-up position with arms straight. Palms should be facing each other. This is the starting position. Begin exercise by lowering yourself down until your chest nearly touches the ground. Pause, then as you push yourself back up, lift your right arm up as you rotate your body to the right. Rotate all the way over until your arm is straight up and your left side is facing the ground. Your body will now look like a "T" on its side. Reverse movements back to starting position. This completes one rep. Repeat on opposite side."

Comment: gymworkouts101 said "-
â–ªï¸Tricep Pushdowns (With V Bar Attachment)
-
TARGETS
1âƒ£Triceps - Standing upright with the torso straight and a very small inclination forward, bring the upper arms close to your body and perpendicular to the floor. The forearms should be pointing up towards the pulley as they hold the bar. This is your starting position. Using the triceps, bring the V- bar down until it touches the front of your thighs and the arms are fully extended perpendicular to the floor. The upper arms should always remain stationary next to your torso and only the forearms should move. Exhale as you perform this movement. After a second hold at the contracted position, bring the bar slowly up to the starting point. Breathe in as you perform this step."

Comment: gymworkouts101 said "-
â–ªï¸Leg Extensions
-
TARGETS
1âƒ£Quads
â–ªï¸- This exercise you will need to use a leg extension machine. First choose your weight and sit on the machine with your legs under the pad (feet pointed forward) and the hands holding the side bars. This will be your starting position.  Tip: You will need to adjust the pad so that it falls on top of your lower leg (just above your feet). Also, make sure that your legs form a 90-degree angle between the lower and upper leg. If the angle is less than 90-degrees then that means the knee is over the toes which in turn creates undue stress at the knee joint. If the machine is designed that way, either look for another machine or just make sure that when you start executing the exercise you stop going down once you hit the 90-degree angle. Using your quadriceps, extend your legs to the maximum as you exhale. Ensure that the rest of the body remains stationary on the seat. Pause a second on the contracted position. Slowly lower the weight back to the original position as you inhale, ensuring that you do not go past the 90-degree angle limit."

Comment: coachbueno said "DIM

DIM (diindolylmethane) is a phytonutrient found in cruciferous vegetables like cabbage, broccoli, Brussels sprouts, cauliflower, and kale. It helps resolving estrogen imbalance by preventing either its drastic increase or decrease. In women, DIM helps maintain testosterone in its active free form which promotes a healthy libido, good mood, and eases PMS symptoms.

Recent studies from the Nutritional Sciences Department at the University of California at Berkeley have shown that DIM has anti-proliferative effects on prostate cancer cells and on human mammary tumor cells. It also has unique immune modulatory properties.

If you have any questions, talk to an expert!"

2-3 haas avocados 
1 juice of a lemon and lime 
1/4 chopped up white onions 
2 cloves of garlic, minced
1/2 teaspoon of salt, pepper and cummin 
1 tablespoon of chopped cilantro 
Mash avocados in a bowl with a fork. Fold in onions, garlic and lime juice. Season with salt, pepper and cummin and then finish with lemon juice to keep guac from browning to quickly. Garnish with cilantro and for extra heat add some chopped jalapeÃ±o ðŸ’"

Comment: yana_yoga said "I have been out of practice for 3 weeks now due to a fractured wrist. This is the first time ever my body is forcing me to take a break. The effects are surfacing in a hurricane that I could not even predict. I have less patience, I am short-tempered, I am closed off, I experience weird insecurities and am not present as I usually am in even simple daily tasks, but best of all, I am able to recognize it all. Comment: yogawithmii said "Day 4 of the #2ndSeries March #Yoga Challenge with @yogiyanni_ & @yogawithmii, sponsored by @yogiiza & @splurgejuicecafe.

How about that first posture of Second Series, #yogis?
For me, that has always been one of the hardest parts of the #practice.
Just have in mind that different asanas will prove easier for some and more difficult for others. 
But I'm #excited to see how everybody's trying their best.

Let's continue with the #challenge, and go to the second #pose of the #Ashtanga Intermediate Series, KrouncÄsana. An interesting position that challenges the flexibility both in the hips as well as the legs.
This #asana requires a lot of patience due to all the things that must be engaged and released at the same time. A very good example of how in #yoga the body works in synergistic ways contracting and relaxing different muscle groups as the same time.

Getting into it can be done through a basic jump or walk through from Down Dog, or a more advanced floating #transition directly into the ready position.
In either case, one leg will be bent at the knee and pointing back, and the opposite leg will be raised and fully extended, ideally with both hands binding in front of the top foot.
Once there, we try to bring the chin to the shin of that raised leg, while pulling the leg towards the torso and maintaining the spine extended as much as possible.
After holding that position for 5 breaths, extend the arms to make room for jumping or walking back to Chaturanga Dandasana.
Then do the same process on the other side.
The #balance between strength and flexibility that's needed for executing each posture will come over time.
Stay disciplined and trust the process.

In this demonstration I'm showing only one side, go check @yogiyanni_ for his version of Heron Posture.

You can post a video or a photo of the posture without worrying about perfect form, just approximate as much as possible.
But most importantly, have #fun and show us how creative you can get with this.

Be sure to include the hashtag #2ndSeries as well as @yogiyanni_, @yogawithmii, @yogiiza & @splurgejuicecafe on each one of your posts.

Shanti à¥ : )
ðŸŽ¶ DJ Drez"
